 Difference between getElementById, getElementsByClassName, querySelector, querySelectorAll

When working with the DOM, these methods are used to select elements, but they behave differently.
getElementById() is used when you want to grab one specific element using its unique ID. Since an ID should only appear once in a page, this method always returns a single element.
getElementsByClassName() is used when multiple elements share the same class. It gives you a collection of elements. One important thing is that this collection updates automatically if the DOM changes.
querySelector() is more flexible. It works like CSS. You can select by ID, class, tag, or even complex selectors. But it only returns the first matching element.
querySelectorAll() is similar to querySelector(), but instead of returning just one, it returns all matching elements. However, unlike getElementsByClassName(), it does not automatically update if the DOM changes.

