 Difference between preventDefault() and stopPropagation()

These two methods are often confused, but they do different things.
preventDefault() stops the browser’s default behavior.
Example: stopping a form from submitting or preventing a link from navigating.
stopPropagation() stops the event from moving upward in the DOM.
It prevents parent elements from receiving the same event.

So:
preventDefault() → stops browser action
stopPropagation() → stops event movement